Both AJAX and `location.replace()` can be used to replace the contents of a page with the contents of a different URL without adding a new page to the navigation stack. However, they work in different ways and have different use cases.

**AJAX**

AJAX (Asynchronous JavaScript and XML) is a technique for dynamically updating a web page without requiring a full page reload. When you use AJAX to load a new page, the URL in the browser's address bar doesn't change, but the page content is updated dynamically.

Here's an example of how to use AJAX to load a new page:
```javascript
// Using jQuery
$.ajax({
  url: 'https://example.com/new-page',
  success: function(data) {
    // Update the page content
    $('#page-content').html(data);
  }
});

// Using vanilla JavaScript
fetch('https://example.com/new-page')
  .then(response => response.text())
  .then(data => {
    // Update the page content
    document.getElementById('page-content').innerHTML = data;
  });
```
